@node Fundamental Structure, Setup Dictionary, Getting Started, Getting Started
@section Fundamental Structure

Lookup can access to various types of dictionaries, which means that
Lookup has several interfaces with dictionaries.  The interface which
actually interacts with dictinaries is called a @dfn{search agent} in
Lookup.  A search agent can treat more than one dictionary; for example,
there are usually several dictionaries in one dictionary server, which
is accessed by one search agent of Lookup.

A search agent provides the feature of accessing a set of dictionaries
correctly, while the appearance of each dictionary is regularized by a
corresponding @dfn{supplement file}, which is a suite of customizations
for each dictionary.  A supplement file is not indispensable for
searching dictionaries properly, but useful to utilize every feature of
Lookup for each dictionary.  The following figure is a rough image of
the structure:

@example
Lookup
  +- Agent 1
  |    +- Dictionary 1 + Supplement 1
  |    +- Dictionary 2 + Supplement 2
  |    +- Dictionary 3 + Supplement 3
  +- Agent 2
  |    +- Dictionary 4
  |    +- Dictionary 5
  +- Agent 3
       +- Dictionary 6
@end example

From the point of view of users, on the other hand, it is important to
be able to use the only dictionaries which the user want to use.  A
@dfn{search module} provides this feature; you can choose your favorite
dictionaries and make groups of dictionaries, which will be used for
searching at once.  You can make several modules at once, and change
them on search time.

Each dictionary has its own @dfn{search methods}, which is strategies to
find entries such as match exactly.  This offen depend on the search
agent of each dictionary, so you need to carefully understand which
dictionary has what methods at first.  You can select and change methods
on search time.

@example
User
  +- Module 1
  |    +- Dictionary 1 + Methods A
  |    +- Dictionary 2 + Methods A
  |    +- Dictionary 4 + Methods B
  |    +- Dictionary 6 + Methods C
  +- Module 2
       +- Dictionary 3 + Methods A
       +- Dictionary 5 + Methods B
       +- Dictionary 6 + Methods C
@end example

All you have to do to use Lookup is to prepare your favorite
dictionaries, to decide what agent you have to use, to figure out what
methods you can use for each dictionary, and to arrange dictionaries
into groups if you want.  It depends on users what is is the best
combination to use dictionary efficientry.  Try to correct dictionaries
and find your way.

